00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:41.240
Let's start front-stabbing.

00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:43.140
Give it to people.

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:44.140
And then they'll learn.

00:42:44.140 --> 00:42:47.150
And it just goes so
against the data.

00:42:47.150 --> 00:42:49.544
I mean, that's a great way to
not just stress individuals

00:42:49.544 --> 00:42:51.710
out and bring them down and
make them want to leave.

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:54.000
There are so many
reasons not to do that.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:56.164
But you can give feedback.

00:42:56.164 --> 00:42:57.080
You can give feedback.

00:42:57.080 --> 00:42:58.913
And you can do it in a
really supportive way

00:42:58.913 --> 00:42:59.880
that helps people grow.

00:42:59.880 --> 00:43:03.350
And it actually makes
them more loyal to you.

00:43:03.350 --> 00:43:04.411
I'll tell you a story.

00:43:04.411 --> 00:43:06.910
Actually, this is a story that
I wrote about in the "Harvard

00:43:06.910 --> 00:43:10.270
Business Review" interviewing
actually my current-- my boss,

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:12.240
who's also a neurosurgeon.

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:15.350
When he was a young
resident, he was

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:20.070
helping the surgeon do this
very complicated brain surgery.

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:22.490
And he was so nervous
that he was sweating.

00:43:22.490 --> 00:43:26.260
And his sweat dripped
into the operation area.

00:43:26.260 --> 00:43:29.004
The surgeon was so angry at him.

00:43:29.004 --> 00:43:30.920
He just kicked him out
of the room-- basically

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:31.711
called him a loser.

00:43:31.711 --> 00:43:33.620
You're never going to
be able to do this.

00:43:33.620 --> 00:43:36.510
Now, he knows that if the sweat
has dropped into the area,

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:41.330
you can very easily irrigate
it, and it can be removed fast.

00:43:41.330 --> 00:43:42.980
Now, the same
thing happened when

00:43:42.980 --> 00:43:45.780
Dr. Doherty was
himself a surgeon

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:48.090
and he had a resident come in.

00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:52.140
And the resident, in one
moment, did not pay attention,

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:55.420
and he pierced a vein
in the operation.

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:57.400
There was blood
all over the brain.

00:43:57.400 --> 00:43:59.890
In the moment, Dr. Doherty
couldn't see what he was doing

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:03.810
and he could have cost him
the life of this person.

00:44:03.810 --> 00:44:07.130
Fortunately he reached in
and blindly clipped that vein

00:44:07.130 --> 00:44:09.060
and was able to save it.

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:13.910
But in that moment, what he
did was he told the resident,

00:44:13.910 --> 00:44:15.630
why don't you go outside?

00:44:15.630 --> 00:44:17.660
You know, just calm yourself.

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:19.730
And when you're ready,
you can come back inside.

00:44:19.730 --> 00:44:22.640
And we'll talk
about how we can--

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:24.960
and I'll teach you a few things.

00:44:24.960 --> 00:44:26.830
What a different response.

00:44:26.830 --> 00:44:28.616
Think about if you
were that resident how

00:44:28.616 --> 00:44:29.990
you would feel
toward that person

00:44:29.990 --> 00:44:30.920
for the rest of your life.

00:44:30.920 --> 00:44:32.794
Obviously, you're
devastated by your mistake.

00:44:32.794 --> 00:44:35.147
But you'll probably be loyal
to that person forever.

00:44:35.147 --> 00:44:36.480
That's inspirational leadership.

00:44:36.480 --> 00:44:37.359
That is true loyalty.

00:44:37.359 --> 00:44:38.900
If someone else
comes along and says,

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:42.170
hey, why don't you come work for
me, they'll be like, I'm sorry.

00:44:42.170 --> 00:44:45.250
I love this person--
literally, right?

