seems productive

00:45:49.020 --> 00:45:50.230
but that will wear you out.

00:45:50.230 --> 00:45:54.011
And I think that that's really
the quandary people are in.

00:45:54.011 --> 00:45:58.250
It's like, well, but my
inbox, I could just empty it.

00:45:58.250 --> 00:46:02.200
There's that desire for the
empty inbox, which never comes.

00:46:02.200 --> 00:46:03.930
We all have it, right?

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:05.670
And yet-- yeah, so
it's more that choice.

00:46:05.670 --> 00:46:07.336
But I think if you're
choosing something

00:46:07.336 --> 00:46:09.870
that nourishes you
that gives you time

00:46:09.870 --> 00:46:12.440
to disengage-- it gives you time
to relax-- it doesn't matter

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:16.250
what it is as long
as it also involves--

00:46:16.250 --> 00:46:19.620
and very much as an individual,
we all know what nourishes us.

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:22.450
For some of us, we need
to go out and be with 20

00:46:22.450 --> 00:46:23.020
best friends.

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:24.500
For others, we need to be alone.

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:26.107
It just depends, so yeah.

00:46:26.107 --> 00:46:26.940
AUDIENCE: Very cool.

00:46:26.940 --> 00:46:27.460
I appreciate that.

00:46:27.460 --> 00:46:28.060
Thank you.

00:46:28.060 --> 00:46:29.060
EMMA SEPPALA: Of course.

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:30.812
AUDIENCE: I wanted
to ask about boredom.

00:46:30.812 --> 00:46:32.520
You were talking a
little bit about that.

00:46:32.520 --> 00:46:35.520
We don't have so much time
sort of off doing nothing.

00:46:35.520 --> 00:46:38.930
And I think you mentioned
being bored or boredom.

00:46:38.930 --> 00:46:41.410
But I'm wondering, is
that sort of the goal,

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:45.340
or is it just
being more relaxed?

00:46:45.340 --> 00:46:47.120
Because I feel like
if I'm bored, I get

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:48.700
stressed out about being bored.

00:46:48.700 --> 00:46:50.408
EMMA SEPPALA: Thank
you for sharing that.

00:46:50.408 --> 00:46:52.290
I need to share
with you this study.

00:46:52.290 --> 00:46:54.710
So in this study--
in the first study,

00:46:54.710 --> 00:46:56.970
participants were
given the choice,

00:46:56.970 --> 00:46:59.320
you can either sit there
and just do nothing,

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:02.840
or you can sit there and
do this really boring task.

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:06.450
People chose to do the
really boring task.

00:47:06.450 --> 00:47:08.980
Then the scientists
looked at, OK, well, here.

00:47:08.980 --> 00:47:10.740
You can sit in this
room, do nothing.

00:47:10.740 --> 00:47:11.710
You can either sit
there and do nothing,

00:47:11.710 --> 00:47:13.640
or you can play with
that machine that

00:47:13.640 --> 00:47:16.806
gives the electric shocks.

00:47:16.806 --> 00:47:18.930
Even those people who said
the electric shocks were

00:47:18.930 --> 00:47:21.170
very disagreeable
and very painful

00:47:21.170 --> 00:47:23.420
preferred to do that than
to sit there and do nothing.

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:26.080
So thank you for
asking that question.

00:47:26.080 --> 00:47:30.700
There is a profound discomfort
sometimes of doing nothing.

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:34.890
And Louis CK, by the way, has
a fantastic episode on that.

00:47:34.890 --> 00:47:39.240
But in some sense, it's also
because of our high pressure

00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:41.550
lifestyle and the
anxiety that can arise.

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:44.220
And I saw this a lot with the
veterans that I worked with.

00:47:44.220 --> 00:47:47.110
If I had just told them
to sit there and meditate

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:50.361
as a first thing that they do,
they may not have taken to it.

00:47:50.361 --> 00:47:52.360
Because the first thing
that we do when we stop,

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:54.750
especially when we used to go,
go, go, go, going all the time,

00:47:54.750 --> 00:47:56.900
is we can feel a lot of
anxiety, like you are saying.

00:47:56.900 --> 00:47:58.150
Thank you for sharing
that, because you're not

00:47:58.150 --> 00:47:58.796
the only one.

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:03.580
And that's why it can
be-- but it's something

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:05.600
that if you sit through
it for a little bit

00:48:05.600 --> 00:48:07.810
and if you just get
used to it, that's

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:09.930
going to be much better
than continuously trying

00:48:09.930 --> 00:48:11.720
to cover that up with activity.

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:15.570
Because that just continues
you into that cycle.

00:48:15.570 --> 00:48:17.050
But again, I would
really recommend

00:48:17.050 --> 00:48:19.090
doing the breathing,
or the meditation,

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:21.750
and some of the things that
are going on here-- learning

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:23.180
to just be without discomfort.

00:48:23.180 --> 00:48:25.700
Because what happens
is it goes away.

00:48:25.700 --> 00:48:29.397
But if we're always covering
it up, it's still there.

00:48:29.397 --> 00:48:30.730
But thanks for bringing that up.

00:48:30.730 --> 00:48:31.680
Because you know what?

00:48:31.680 --> 00:48:34.580
I think pretty much
everyone feels that.

00:48:34.580 --> 00:48:37.690
And that's probably
the reason why

00:48:37.690 --> 00:48:39.280
we so much need to
distract ourselves,

00:48:39.280 --> 00:48:41.310
even if it's work all the time.

00:48:41.310 --> 00:48:41.840
Yeah.

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:44.546
But if you look at kids, kids
are great people to-- they're

00:48:44.546 --> 00:48:46.420
the most creative
individuals in our society.

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:48.200
They come up with--
you give them nothing

00:48:48.200 --> 00:48:50.532
and they've created a
whole kingdom out of it.

00:48:50.532 --> 00:48:52.740
And they are constantly in
that state of daydreaming.

00:48:52.740 --> 00:48:54.540
They're constantly present.

00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:57.485
They're constantly
connected with one another.

00:48:57.485 --> 00:48:58.860
It's just something
very natural.

00:48:58.860 --> 00:49:01.220
So that means we have it
too because we were kids

00:49:01.220 --> 00:49:02.633
once a long time ago.

00:49:02.633 --> 00:49:03.672
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:49:03.672 --> 00:49:04.880
EMMA SEPPALA: You're welcome.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:06.671
AUDIENCE: So since you
brought up children,

00:49:06.671 --> 00:49:12.050
I have a question where I found
this theme among parents where

00:49:12.050 --> 00:49:15.109
there's kind of a desire that,
well now that they're kids

00:49:15.109 --> 00:49:16.900
and they can do all
these different things,

00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:19.765
this is the time to have lots
of variety, lots of-- right?

00:49:19.765 --> 00:49:21.890
Because when they get older
and they get into a job

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:23.810
they'll only do one thing
for the rest of their lives.

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:26.620
So let's give them a chance now
to do soccer, tennis, swimming,

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:28.220
ballet, and everything.

00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:32.700
But then there's the question
of the over-programming.

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:35.050
And I'm wondering
to what extent do

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:39.300
you think there's a benefit to
doing lots of things as opposed

00:49:39.300 --> 00:49:44.375
to just doing one
thing in an open time?

00:49:44.375 --> 00:49:46.750
EMMA SEPPALA: Honestly, every
talk I've given on the book

00:49:46.750 --> 00:49:49.120
so far, I've been asked
these questions from parents.

00:49:49.120 --> 00:49:51.210
And it's so poignant.

00:49:51.210 --> 00:49:52.970
It's such a good question.

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:56.490
I think that-- one of the women
that I last week she asked,

00:49:56.490 --> 00:49:57.996
I could see pain in her eyes.

00:49:57.996 --> 00:50:00.370
She was like, I really want
my child to get into Harvard.

00:50:00.370 --> 00:50:02.650
So I have to get her
to do all this stuff.

00:50:02.650 --> 00:50:04.550
And yet, my child
is so stressed.

00:50:04.550 --> 00:50:06.730
It's so sad.

00:50:06.730 --> 00:50:11.290
I would say have her child
do what makes them happy.

00:50:11.290 --> 00:50:15.610
And if it's one activity, and
then they give them time to me.

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:19.690
Give them time to be a
child first and foremost.

00:50:19.690 --> 00:50:21.080
It's so interesting.

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:24.360
I shared this [INAUDIBLE]
I was an undergrad at Yale

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:26.420
and a grad student at
Columbia and Stanford.

00:50:26.420 --> 00:50:27.722
And I worked at Stanford.

00:50:27.722 --> 00:50:29.180
And then I worked
at the University

00:50:29.180 --> 00:50:32.510
of Wisconsin Madison,
which is all the best

00:50:32.510 --> 00:50:35.600
students in Wisconsin
get into that school.

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:38.490
But it's obviously not like
the Harvard/Yale caliber.

00:50:38.490 --> 00:50:42.055
Where were the students most
balanced, most happy, most

00:50:42.055 --> 00:50:44.680
in touch with their values, most
in touch with their community?

00:50:44.680 --> 00:50:45.250
In Wisconsin.

00:50:48.230 --> 00:50:51.120
And the Stanford and the
Yale students-- so talented.

00:50:51.120 --> 00:50:55.572
And they're geniuses
in so many ways.

00:50:55.572 --> 00:50:57.530
And they're so-- you
know, I'm sure many of you

00:50:57.530 --> 00:50:59.450
are students who have
been to those places.

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:01.480
And yet, the stress
level is so high.

00:51:01.480 --> 00:51:03.220
They haven't learned
how to relax.

00:51:03.220 --> 00:51:05.996
And also, there's a sense of
disconnect from the community.

00:51:05.996 --> 00:51:08.370
And this is a piece of research
that I haven't shared yet

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:11.650
but that I want to share, is
that the most important thing

00:51:11.650 --> 00:51:14.390
after food and shelter for our
happiness, well-being, health,

00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:17.080
and longevity, is connections--
social connections,

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:18.890
positive connections--
with other people.

00:51:18.890 --> 00:51:21.411
And yet, when we're constantly
being told, achieve.

00:51:21.411 --> 00:51:21.910
Be the best.

00:51:21.910 --> 00:51:22.530
Be number one.

00:51:22.530 --> 00:51:25.170
Go, go, go-- we
are very stressed,

00:51:25.170 --> 00:51:27.320
and we're really self-focused.

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:29.250
I'm not saying we're
selfish, but we're

00:51:29.250 --> 00:51:30.410
self-focused naturally.

00:51:30.410 --> 00:51:33.080
And when you're stressed, your
self-focus increases naturally.

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:35.360
This is something-- imagine
our ancestors running away

00:51:35.360 --> 00:51:36.550
from some predator.

00:51:36.550 --> 00:51:38.810
They'd better be focused
in that moment, right?

00:51:38.810 --> 00:51:41.130
And yet, over time
with chronic stress,

00:51:41.130 --> 00:51:43.280
and this self-focus
actually leads to misery.

00:51:43.280 --> 00:51:46.260
One in four Americans
says they have no one

00:51:46.260 --> 00:51:48.480
to speak to about
a personal problem.

00:51:48.480 --> 00:51:51.970
One in four people you
meet is profoundly lonely.

00:51:51.970 --> 00:51:55.990
So I'm going to a little bit
of tangent, but not really.

00:51:55.990 --> 00:51:58.100
Let's teach our
children to be happy.

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:00.220
Let's value their happiness.

00:52:00.220 --> 00:52:01.330
They'll be more creative.

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:02.454
They'll be more productive.

00:52:02.454 --> 00:52:04.740
They'll work because they
are interested in the topic,

00:52:04.740 --> 00:52:07.090
not because they have
to do it because we

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:09.035
have to get into Harvard.

00:52:09.035 --> 00:52:10.097
You know what I mean?

00:52:10.097 --> 00:52:10.930
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:10.930 --> 00:52:12.480
EMMA SEPPALA: I think it's
such an important question,

00:52:12.480 --> 00:52:14.280
and I'm going to try--
I've been drafting

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:17.500
an op-ed about it
because I've received

00:52:17.500 --> 00:52:18.850
this question at every talk.

00:52:18.850 --> 00:52:21.340
And parents feel
like, I have to keep

00:52:21.340 --> 00:52:23.894
my child on the correct route.

00:52:23.894 --> 00:52:25.810
But at the same time,
there's this disconnect.

00:52:25.810 --> 00:52:27.550
So thank you for asking.

00:52:27.550 --> 00:52:28.479
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:28.479 --> 00:52:30.020
MELISSA CHOBAN: But
thank you, again.

00:52:30.020 --> 00:52:32.750
And yeah, may
happiness be yours.

00:52:32.750 --> 00:52:35.800
[APPLAUSE]

